cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "A signed-direction invariant for triangle tilings, and the exclusion of primes congruent to 3 modulo 4"
authors:
  - family-names: Bonfioli
    given-names: Vico
    email: vicobonfioli@gmail.com
abstract: >-
  A translation-invariant, signed-direction tiling functional that, within the 2pi/3 branch of
  Laczkovich's classification of triangle tilings, proves that no prime number of 2pi/3 tiles tiles
  an isosceles triangle (for every prime, where only a finite bound was previously known). With a
  self-contained reduction of the scalene shapes, this completes the exclusion of primes congruent
  to 3 modulo 4 as numbers of congruent triangles tiling a triangle, conditional on the cited
  classification; in particular no triangle can be cut into 19 congruent triangles. The
  prime case of the full problem is thereby complete (a prime occurs iff p = 2, 3, or 1 mod 4),
  the admissible spectrum of each sporadic branch is determined (with a parity refinement), every
  value up to 32 is settled (14, 15, 21, 22, 30 are excluded, by branch sweeps and exhaustive
  exact searches), and N = 46, the sharpest test of Zhang's completeness conjecture, is excluded
  in agreement with that conjecture. The arithmetic and combinatorial layer is machine-checked in
  Lean 4 with Mathlib. Developed with AI assistance
  (Anthropic Claude); presented for peer review.
keywords:
  - triangle tiling
  - Erdős problem 634
  - congruent triangles
  - discrete geometry
  - combinatorics
  - tiling invariant
  - Lean
  - formal verification
license: CC-BY-4.0
year: 2026
